<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-04T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-04T02:00:00-05:00" n="881" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d881">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2311: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-04T14:00:00+07:00">October 4, 1940—2
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 4—10:42 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>503. I perceive no objection to Butrick discussing the proposal
                                contained in his 1025, October 3, 1 p.m. Until I am certain that the
                                Chinese Government will not give its consent to such a proceeding I
                                must doubtless accept it if it were found feasible and put into
                                effect without involving the necessity of its consent.</p>
                            <p>Sent to the Department. Repeated to Peiping, Shanghai.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>